l server-only function first:\n\n```text\nprojectAgentTrail(request: AgentTrailProjectionRequest) -> AgentTrailProjection\n```\n\nThe request should contain the prepared repo path or GitMeta source, resolved\nmetadata OID, PR facts, limits, and projection version. The response should be\nonly the public Agent Trail projection. The native layer should not perform\nGitHub HTTP, own snapshot retentio\n[TRUNCATED]\ntorage interpretation. A future lower-level `git-meta-lib` API could accept an\nexplicit object database or in-memory GitMeta source, but that is a separate\nlibrary-design project.\n\nIf Forge's deployment target cannot provide a writable cache directory, `git`,\nnative addon loading, and enough request/worker time to fetch and materialize\nGitMeta, do not force Agent Trail generation into this Next.js app. Split the\ngenerator into a separate service or worker with durable local storage and have\nForge call it over HTTP or a queue. Forge can still own the public routes and UI,\nbut the repository cache and projection generation should live where the runtime\nfits the workload.\n\n## Repository Placement Decision\n\nKeep the public route, API facade, and eventual UI in Forge. Put the projection\ngenerator in Forge only if production runs as a stateful Node/container service\nwith:\n\n- writable cache storage for scratch Git repositories\n- `git` available at runtime\n- native `.node` addon loading for the dedicated Agent Trail NAPI package\n- enough request or worker time for fetch/materialize/projection work\n- per-repository locking and cache cleanup\n\nIf Forge is serverless, edge-like, ephemeral-only, or cannot load native addons,\ncreate a separate Agent Trail generator service/repo and let Forge call it. This\nfeature is closer to a Git cache/projection worker than to a normal Next.js route\nhandler.\n\nGiven the current repository, the safer default is: Forge owns the website and\nJSON API contract; a separate generator service owns local repositories